## Understanding the Scale

**TN 6 - Easy Tasks**
Trained characters succeed routinely. Untrained characters have reasonable chances. This represents tasks that require some capability but aren't particularly challenging—climbing a knotted rope, picking a simple lock, recalling common knowledge.

A Competent (+0) character with average attributes (+0) succeeds about 72% of the time. A Professional (+1) character with +1 attribute succeeds about 91% of the time. Use this TN when you want trained characters to succeed reliably while giving untrained characters fighting chances.

**TN 8 - Standard Tasks**
The baseline difficulty. This represents meaningful challenges for trained characters—climbing a rough wall, picking a standard lock, recalling specialized knowledge. Success isn't guaranteed but is achievable with competence.

A Competent (+0) character with average attributes succeeds about 42% of the time. A Professional (+1) character with +1 attribute succeeds about 72% of the time. Most skill checks should use TN 8 unless there's specific reason for easier or harder.

**TN 10 - Difficult Tasks**
These require significant expertise or exceptional natural talent. Climbing a sheer wall, picking a complex lock, recalling obscure lore. Competent characters struggle; professionals succeed regularly.

A Competent (+0) character with average attributes succeeds about 17% of the time. A Professional (+1) character with +1 attribute succeeds about 42% of the time. Use this TN when tasks should challenge even skilled characters.

**TN 12 - Very Difficult Tasks**
Only experts and exceptionally talented individuals succeed reliably. Climbing an overhanging cliff, picking a masterwork lock, recalling legendary lore. These tasks push the boundaries of what's achievable through skill alone.

A Professional (+1) character with +1 attribute succeeds about 17% of the time. An Expert (+2) character with +2 attribute succeeds about 42% of the time. Reserve this TN for tasks that should feel genuinely difficult even for skilled specialists.

**TN 14 - Nearly Impossible**
The limit of what skill and talent can achieve. Anything harder than this requires magical assistance, legendary abilities, or simply can't be done. Climbing a glass-smooth wall, picking an unpickable lock, recalling knowledge lost to history.

An Expert (+2) character with +2 attribute succeeds about 17% of the time. A Master (+3) character with +3 attribute succeeds about 42% of the time. Use this TN sparingly—only when you want to communicate "this is nearly impossible."

